<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Global Terrorism Experts: Prepare for Long Struggle, Fight Back With Education and Vigilance</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Stephanie Constantin
		
		<span class="date">Oct. 15, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:freeman@mail.ucf.edu">Mark Freeman, Global Perspectives</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0935</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.ucfglobalperspectives.org">UCF Office of Global Perspectives</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>A group of the worlds leading terrorism experts conveyed a sober message to a diverse UCF audience of about 325 people Thursday: The fight against the current wave of terrorism will be a long one, lasting multiple generations. In addition, the world, especially the United States, can never expect to fully eradicate terrorism, as it has been a part of human society for millennia, panelists said.</p><p>The speakers were part of a large group of terrorism specialists from a dozen countries who had gathered at UCF for two days of private discussions organized by the UCF Global Perspectives Office and Terrorism Studies Program. Those discussions will be published as a white paper, which is scheduled for release in early 2008. The public forums speakers shared some of the conferences preliminary findings, along with personal observations. </p><p>Brian Jenkins, a senior figure at the RAND Corporation and one of the worlds leading authorities on terrorism, opened the forum by discussing the differences between the ways that Western cultures and many modern terrorists define war. He explained that the latter considers the process as ongoing and believes that war is life. This is a stark contrast to the customary American perspective on war, which includes a definite starting point and end date, along with recognizable targets. </p><p>Jenkins, who founded the RAND Corporations terrorism research program in 1972 and has served as an advisor to the federal government and private sector on terrorism, also pointed out that domestic perceptions of terrorism are fraught with fear. According to Jenkins, the message our news media tend to portray is that were all going to die, but keep shopping.</p><p>Stephen Sloan, a fellow and university professor at UCF and director of the Terrorism Studies Program, reinforced the idea that this war will last long and that terrorism -- much like theft and murder -- will never truly cease to exist. We cannot afford to succumb to fear; if we do, the terrorists win, he said. </p><p>Magnus Ranstorp, the research director at the Center for Asymmetric Threat Studies of the Swedish National Defense College, related radical Islamic ideology to the tensions in todays world. He described the appeal of radical Islamic terrorist organizations as coming from three narratives: the narrative of humiliation that some Muslims perceive from the Wests being at war with Islam; the narrative of violence that offers to transport humiliation to victory; and the narrative of the projection of emotionally powerful imagery found in the news media. </p><p>Sebestyen Gorka, the founding director of the Institute for Transitional Democracy and International Security in Budapest, Hungary, echoed others in discussing the futility of trying to eliminate terrorism, but he insisted on the necessity and possibility of managing it. Although there will be no peace treaty at the end, a commitment for the duration is essential, he said.</p><p>Providing a U.S. government view on terrorism, Mark Thompson, the deputy coordinator for operations in the Office of the Coordinator for Counter-Terrorism at the U.S. Department of State, spoke about how we need to be more unconventional in our efforts when it comes to going after terrorist safe-heavens, including utilizing the Internet and news media. Terrorists are a lot better at getting their message out, he said, in stark contrast to the American news media process. </p><p>Education, which every other panelist also underscored, is the key to combating this ideological warfare, Thompson said. He encouraged everyone in the audience to get more involved in international issues, whether by joining the U.S. military, the U.S. Foreign Service, the Peace Corps or other internationally oriented organizations. </p><p>Fernando Reinares, a former senior advisor on anti-terrorism to the government of Spain and currently a professor at the Universidad Rey Juan Carlos in Madrid, used examples from his own experience -- including the Madrid bombings of a few years ago -- to highlight the terrorist threat. Spain is used to terrorism, he said, making reference to the Basque group ETA. Reinares mentioned that since the Madrid bombings, terrorism has gotten worse rather than better, with some of the causes being the radicalization of first- and second-generation immigrants. </p><p>In his concluding remarks, Sloan reminded the audience that terrorism is not a mindless act of violence but rather a purposeful act to achieve political goals. Terrorism is aimed at the people watching and at the survivors of bombings and killings, and the terrorists goal is to instill fear and intimidation. </p><p>Sponsors of the forum included the UCF Global Perspectives Office, UCF Terrorism Studies Program, Center for Asymmetric Threat Studies of the Swedish National Defense College, Institute for Transitional Democracy and International Security, UCF Political Science Department, UCF Criminal Justice and Legal Studies Department, UCF International Services Center and the Global Connections Foundation.</p>
		
	
